<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<gpx xmlns="http://www.topografix.com/GPX/1/1">
   <wpt lat="50.3494895" lon="6.9748324"><ele>546.0</ele><name>Döttinger Höhe</name><desc>Named after nearby village of Döttingen.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 20km, End: 20.8km
Notable Features: Named after Döttingen village, Final section of track</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3542336" lon="6.9862747"><ele>559.0</ele><name>Galgenkopf</name><desc>Former execution place of Counts of Nürburg with public gallows.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 19km, End: 20km
Notable Features: Former execution site, Public gallows location, Counts of Nürburg history</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3581251" lon="6.9861031"><ele>533.0</ele><name>Schwalbenschwanz</name><desc>Name from swallow's tail shape from bird's eye view. Small Carousel is smaller steep concrete curve leading to Galgenkopf.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 18km, End: 19km
Alternative Names: kleines Karussell
Notable Features: Swallow's tail shape, Small Carousel, Steep concrete curve</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.362853" lon="6.9971371"><ele>547.0</ele><name>kleiner Sprunghügel</name><desc>Small and Large Jumping Hills. Pflanzgarten II renamed Stefan-Bellof-S in 2013. Stefan Bellof's 1983 record 6:11.13 in Porsche 956 remains unbeaten.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 17km, End: 18km
Alternative Names: großer Sprunghügel, Stefan-Bellof-S, Pflanzgarten II
Notable Features: Small Jumping Hill, Large Jumping Hill, Stefan Bellof memorial, Unbeaten lap record 6:11.13 (1983), Porsche 956</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3686975" lon="7.0041516"><ele>555.0</ele><name>Brünnchen</name><desc>Spring area for Herschbroich water. Eiskurve particularly slippery in bad weather. Gardens/fields of Counts of Nürburg.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 16km, End: 17km
Alternative Names: Eiskurve, Pflanzgarten
Notable Features: Spring water source, Ice Curve (slippery), Counts of Nürburg gardens</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3751024" lon="7.0011261"><ele>599.0</ele><name>Hedwigshöhe</name><desc>Named after Hedwig Creutz, wife of Nürburgring forefather. Wippermann from bobbing vehicles. Eschbach from stream and village, many ash trees.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 15km, End: 16km
Alternative Names: Wippermann, Eschbach
Notable Features: Named after Hedwig Creutz, Vehicle bobbing area, Eschbach stream, Former ash tree forests</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3733371" lon="6.9912824"><ele>567.0</ele><name>Posten 147</name><desc>Small hut (alpine pasture) between roundabout and Hohe Acht. Hohe Acht leads past highest Eifel mountain (747m). Second highest point on Nordschleife.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 14km, End: 15km
Alternative Names: Hohe Acht
Notable Features: Post 147 hut, Highest Eifel mountain (747m), Second highest point on track</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3745613" lon="6.9884327"><ele>544.0</ele><name>Klostertalkurve</name><desc>Junction to steep section. Steilstrecke 27% gradient for vehicle tests (no longer used). Karussell named after Rudolf Caracciola, first to drive curve completely inside.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 13km, End: 14km
Alternative Names: Steilstrecke, Caracciola-Karussell
Notable Features: 27% gradient steep section, Vehicle testing area (unused), Caracciola Carousel, Rudolf Caracciola legacy</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3736723" lon="6.9757578"><ele>471.0</ele><name>Mutkurve</name><desc>Only bravest drivers take bend to full (Courage Curve). Order of St. John in Monastery Valley in 14th century.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 12km, End: 13km
Alternative Names: Klostertal
Notable Features: Courage Curve, 14th century Order of St. John, Monastery Valley, Hermit monk history</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3761801" lon="6.9621885"><ele>403.0</ele><name>Kesselchen</name><desc>Route leads through basin.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 11km, End: 12km
Notable Features: Basin topography</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3794985" lon="6.9555232"><ele>364.0</ele><name>ExTal</name><desc>ExTal between ExMühle and mine. Bergwerk: lead and silver mine until early 20th century.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 10km, End: 11km
Alternative Names: Bergwerk
Notable Features: Former lead and silver mine, Mining until early 1900s</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.376615" lon="6.9438614"><ele>371.0</ele><name>Wehrseifen</name><desc>Valley training ground for militia. ExMühle from mill outside Adenau. Breidscheid village, lowest point of Nordschleife.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 9km, End: 10km
Alternative Names: ExMühle, Breidscheid
Notable Features: Former militia training ground, Mill outside Adenau, Lowest point of Nordschleife, Alternative access road</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.374673" lon="6.933832"><ele>439.0</ele><name>Kallenhard</name><desc>Name from overgrowth (Hart = tree-covered slope). Spiegelkurve where drivers hit mirrors. Dreifach-Rechts = three consecutive right bends (miss-hit-miss).</desc><cmt>Section Start: 8km, End: 9km
Alternative Names: Spiegelkurve, Dreifach-Rechts
Notable Features: Tree-covered slope origin, Mirror Curve, Triple Right turns, Miss-hit-miss technique</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3681853" lon="6.9334504"><ele>468.0</ele><name>Metzgesfeld</name><desc>Name from land register designation.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 7km, End: 8km
Notable Features: Land register designation origin</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3608766" lon="6.9266774"><ele>485.0</ele><name>Fuchsröhre</name><desc>Fox crawled into drainage pipe during construction. Depression called compression. Adenauer Forest area.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 6km, End: 7km
Alternative Names: Kompression, Adenauer Forst
Notable Features: Fox Tube origin story, Compression depression, Adenauer Forest</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3558919" lon="6.9238678"><ele>557.0</ele><name>Schwedenkreuz</name><desc>1638 mayor slain by Swedish soldiers, cross still stands. Aremberg village/mountain nearby. Postbrücke from post road crossing.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 5km, End: 6km
Alternative Names: Aremberg, Postbrücke
Notable Features: Swedish Cross memorial (1638), Aremberg village/mountain, Post road bridge crossing</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3477643" lon="6.9264883"><ele>584.0</ele><name>Flugplatz</name><desc>Former gliding area to left of track. Kottenborn name from village.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 4km, End: 5km
Alternative Names: Kottenborn
Notable Features: Former gliding airfield, Named after Kottenborn village</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3404449" lon="6.9335505"><ele>582.0</ele><name>Hocheichen</name><desc>Dense oak forests, some cut for track. Quiddelbacher Höhe runs along ridge near Quiddelbach village.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 3km, End: 4km
Alternative Names: Quiddelbacher Höhe
Notable Features: Former dense oak forests, Ridge near Quiddelbach village</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.337382" lon="6.945312"><ele>602.0</ele><name>Hatzenbach</name><desc>Stream of same name runs alongside track.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 2km, End: 3km
Notable Features: Hatzenbach stream runs alongside</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.33966" lon="6.955086"><ele>599.0</ele><name>Hohenrain</name><desc>Runs along high meadow/field boundary. T13 is old grandstand facility. Former start with pits. Highest point of Nordschleife.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 1km, End: 2km
Alternative Names: T13
Notable Features: Highest point of Nordschleife, Former start/finish line, Old grandstand T13, Former pit area</cmt></wpt><wpt lat="50.3459947" lon="6.9656535"><ele>572.0</ele><name>Driveway</name><desc>New entrance for tourist trips on Döttinger Höhe. Antoniusbuche: Until 1935, huge beech tree with St. Anthony altar. Tiergarten used to be burial ground for war animals.</desc><cmt>Section Start: 0km, End: 1km
Alternative Names: Antoniusbuche, Tiergarten
Notable Features: New tourist entrance, Antoniusbrücke, Former beech tree location, Animal burial ground</cmt></wpt><trk>
